<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE unit
  SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<unit xmlns="Unit"
      xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
      unitid="Illu_RotationR3"
      xsi:schemaLocation="Unit file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Unit.xsd">
   <titles>
      <title>Rotation of 3-Space - Illustration</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>How do we describe the rotation of space about an arbitrary axis in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>?</para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/RotationGeneral.jpg"/>
               <extended.caption>
                  <image.mapping>
                     <area shape="rect" coord="0,0,200,100"/>
                  </image.mapping>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>In this picture, take <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{r}</latex>
                           </math> to be the unit vector pointing upward, take <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{a}_1</latex>
                           </math> to be any unit vector perpendicular to <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{r}</latex>
                           </math>, for example the one point toward you. Finally take <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{a}_2</latex>
                           </math> to be the cross product <math>
                              <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{r} }{ \Vect{a}_1 }</latex>
                           </math>. This is the third vector in the picture.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </extended.caption>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>Our strategy is to reduce a rotation about an arbitrary axis through the angle <math>
                     <latex>\alpha</latex>
                  </math> to a rotation about a coordinate axis:</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Introduce an ordered orthonormal coordinate system <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{a},\Vect{b},\Vect{n})</latex>
                        </math> such that the axis of rotation has the direction of the basis vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Using <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates, we describe the given rotation as if it were a rotation of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math> about the <math>
                           <latex>z</latex>
                        </math>-axis.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                        </math> gets transformed into <math>
                           <latex>\cos\alpha \Vect{a} + \sin\theta \Vect{b}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{b}</latex>
                        </math> gets transformed into <math>
                           <latex>-\sin\alpha \Vect{a} +\cos\theta \Vect{b}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}</latex>
                        </math> gets transformed into <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>In <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates this rotation is therefore represented by</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{B}}\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
\cos \alpha &amp; -\sin\alpha &amp; 0 \\
\sin\alpha &amp; \cos \alpha &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
                  </math.display>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Let <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}}</latex>
                        </math> denote the matrix which converts from standard coordinates to  <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates. Then the matrix describing the given rotation in standard coordinates is</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{R}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{S}}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}} \Mtrx{R}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{B}} \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B} \EuScript{S}}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
               </li>
            </ol>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
</unit>